Over a period of about 24 h the two reagents vaporized in the warm zone and condensed in the cooler zone The tube was then inverted and the sublimation cycle repeated This mixing process was continued until the sublimate exhibited a homogeneous appearance The doped material grows as long, silver-black rods with lavetous, well-faceted, hexagonal faces The crystals are both air- and heat-sensitive but can be handled in dry air (for X-ray mounting purposes) for 1-2 min without decomposition The elemental composition of the material has been established by X-ray crystallography and by numerous elemental (C, H, N, and I) analyses Two typical analyses (with the formula expressed in terms of the numbers of iodines per six HCN3S3 units) are provided: 1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 73; H, 0.78; N, 21, 81; 1, 18.12 Found: (1) C, 9, 73; H, 1.31; N, 21.86; I, 17.94; (2) C, 9,31; H, 1.02; N, 21.82; I, 17.97;

### X-ray Measurements 
All X-ray data were collected on an ENRAF-Nonics CAD-4 diffractometer with monochromated M6 Ka (_a_) = 0.71073 A) radiation Crystals were sealed in epoxy and sealed in glass tubes Data were collected using a 6/26 technique The structures were solved using direct methods/SHELX and refined by full-matrix least squares which minimized 2N(AP) A summary of crystallographic data is provided in Table 4 Special notes on both structures follow 
